# Drizzle ORM Postgres Error Handling

Drizzle ORM wraps native Postgres errors inside a `cause` property. When catching database errors (e.g. unique constraint violations), **always check both levels**:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — only checks top-level, misses Drizzle-wrapped errors
try {
  await db.execute(sql`INSERT INTO ...`);
} catch (err: unknown) {
  const pgErr = err as { code?: string };
  if (pgErr.code === "23505") {
    // This may NEVER match because Drizzle puts code on err.cause
  }
}

// ✅ GOOD — checks both top-level and cause
try {
  await db.execute(sql`INSERT INTO ...`);
} catch (err: unknown) {
  const pgCode = (err as { code?: string }).code
    ?? (err as { cause?: { code?: string } }).cause?.code;
  if (pgCode === "23505") {
    // Duplicate key — handle gracefully
  }
}
```

## Common Postgres error codes

| Code | Meaning | Typical use |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `23505` | Unique constraint violation | Duplicate key / upsert logic |
| `23503` | Foreign key violation | Missing referenced row |
| `23502` | Not-null violation | Required field missing |
| `42P01` | Undefined table | Table doesn't exist |
